This paper proposes a model for clinical concept extraction using contextual word embedding and deep learning techniques. The paper focuses on natural language processing (NLP) and machine learning (ML) methods for clinical text analysis, which are typically covered in the cs.CL (Computation and Language) sub-category. The use of contextual word embedding also suggests a potential overlap with the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves the training of a bidirectional LSTM-CRF model, which is a popular deep learning architecture for sequence labeling tasks, indicating a possible connection to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. The evaluation of the proposed model on a benchmark dataset also suggests a potential relevance to the cs.IR (Information Retrieval) sub-category. Finally, the use of deep learning techniques for clinical concept extraction may also relate to the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category.
